'''Kooline Station''', often referred to as '''Kooline''', is a pastoral lease that operates as a [[cattle station]].

It is located about {{convert|140|km|mi|0}} south of [[Pannawonica, Western Australia|Pannawonica]] and  {{convert|200|km|mi|0}} south east of [[Onslow, Western Australia|Onslow]] in the [[Pilbara]] region of [[Western Australia]].

Kooline occupies an area of {{convert|2043|km2|sqmi|0}} with the [[Ashburton River (Western Australia)|Ashburton River]] running through the property for a distance of about {{convert|90|km|mi|0}}. The property shares boundaries with [[Ashburton Downs]], [[Glenflorrie]], [[Ullawarra]], [[Wyloo]] and Amelia Stations as well as vacant [[crown land]].<ref name=R1>{{cite web|url=http://archive.agric.wa.gov.au/objtwr/imported_assets/content/lwe/rpm/catman/62%20part%202.pdf|title=Station Reports|year=1980|accessdate=5 April 2014|publisher=[[Department of Agriculture and Food (Western Australia)|Department of Agriculture]]}}</ref>

In 1921 the property was owned by Mr Sanderson, Michael Corbett and his two brothers, who experienced a good season<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article74956472 |title=Asburton |newspaper=[[The Northern Times]] |location=Carnarvon, Western Australia |date=26 March 1921 |accessdate=2 May 2014 |page=5 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> followed by a [[drought]] that broke in early 1923.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23886013 |title=Rural Gossip |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=29 January 1923 |accessdate=2 May 2014 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>


